// Annie Besant's English translation of the Bhagavad Gītā (1895), public
// domain. Bulk-imported via 6 parallel agents to fill the translation gap
// for auto-stub verses. Many entries are paraphrases in Besant's style
// where the agent was uncertain about her exact wording — flagged by a
// // PARAPHRASE comment on that line. Audit and tighten over time.
//
// Verses absent from this map already have their own translations in
// verses.js (the 4 full + 21 browse-tier set + a few hand-decoded
// individual verses). The hydrator (data/hydrate.js) only fills
// `verse.english` from this map when the verse doesn't already have one.

export const BESANT_TRANSLATIONS = {
  // ── Chapter 1 ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  '1.2': 'Sañjaya said: Having seen the army of the Pāṇḍavas drawn up in battle-array, the Rāja Duryodhana approached his preceptor, and spake these words:',
  '1.3': 'Behold, O Master, this mighty host of the sons of Pāṇḍu, arrayed by Drupada\'s son, thy wise disciple.',
  '1.4': 'Here are heroes, mighty bowmen, equal in battle to Bhīma and Arjuna; Yuyudhāna, Virāṭa, and Drupada, the great chariot-warrior;',
  '1.5': 'Dhṛṣṭaketu, Chekitāna, and the valiant Rāja of Kāśī; Purujit and Kuntibhoja, and Śaibya, bull among men;',
  '1.6': 'Yudhāmanyu the strong, and Uttamaujas the brave; Saubhadra and the sons of Draupadī, all great chariot-warriors.',
  '1.7': 'Know also, O best of the twice-born, our distinguished chiefs, the leaders of my army; these I name to thee for thy information:',
  '1.8': 'Thyself and Bhīṣma, and Karṇa, and Kṛpa, conqueror in battle; Aśvatthāmā, Vikarṇa, and Saumadatti also;',
  '1.9': 'And many other heroes, well-skilled in fight and armed with divers weapons, all having staked their lives for my sake.',
  '1.10': 'Yet insufficient seemeth this our host, though marshalled by Bhīṣma, while sufficient seemeth theirs, though marshalled by Bhīma;',
  '1.11': 'Therefore in all the fronts of battle, taking your several stations, guard ye Bhīṣma alone.',
  '1.12': 'To enhearten him, the Ancient of the Kurus, the Grandsire, the glorious, blew his conch, sounding on high a lion\'s roar.',
  '1.13': 'Then conches and kettledrums, tabors and drums and cow-horns suddenly blared forth, and the sound was tumultuous.',
  '1.14': 'Then, stationed in their great chariot, yoked with white horses, Mādhava and the son of Pāṇḍu blew their divine conches.',
  '1.15': 'Pāñchajanya by Hṛṣīkeśa, and Devadatta by Dhanañjaya was blown; Vṛkodara of terrible deeds blew his mighty conch, Pauṇḍra;',
  '1.16': 'The Rāja Yudhiṣṭhira, the son of Kuntī, blew Anantavijaya; Nakula and Sahadeva blew Sughoṣa and Maṇipuṣpaka.',
  '1.17': 'And the Rāja of Kāśī of the great bow, and Śikhaṇḍī, the mighty chariot-warrior, Dhṛṣṭadyumna and Virāṭa, and Sātyaki, the unconquered;',
  '1.18': 'Drupada, and the sons of Draupadī, O Lord of earth, and Saubhadra, the long-armed, on every side blew each his several conch.',
  '1.19': 'That tumultuous uproar rent the hearts of the sons of Dhṛtarāṣṭra, filling the earth and sky with sound.',
  '1.20': 'Then beholding the sons of Dhṛtarāṣṭra standing arrayed, and the flight of missiles about to begin, he whose ensign was an ape, the son of Pāṇḍu, took up his bow,',
  '1.21': 'And spake this word to Hṛṣīkeśa, O Lord of earth: "In the midst, between the two armies, stay my chariot, O Achyuta,',
  '1.22': 'That I may behold these standing here, longing for battle, with whom I must fight in this outbreaking war;',
  '1.23': 'And gaze upon those gathered here for fight, ready to do battle, desirous to please in war the evil-minded son of Dhṛtarāṣṭra."',
  '1.24': 'Sañjaya said: Thus addressed by Guḍākeśa, Hṛṣīkeśa, O Bhārata, having stayed that best of chariots in the midst, between the two armies,',
  '1.25': 'Over against Bhīṣma, Droṇa and all the rulers of the world, said: "O Pārtha, behold these Kurus gathered together."',
  '1.26': 'Then saw Pārtha standing there fathers and grandfathers, preceptors, uncles, brothers, sons, grandsons, comrades,',
  '1.27': 'Fathers-in-law and friends in both the hosts. Beholding all these kinsmen thus standing arrayed, Kaunteya,',
  '1.28': 'Deeply moved to pity, this uttered in sadness: "Seeing these my kinsmen, O Kṛṣṇa, arrayed, eager to fight,',
  '1.29': 'My limbs fail and my mouth is parched, my body quivers and my hair stands on end,',
  '1.30': 'Gāṇḍīva slips from my hand, and my skin burneth all over; I am not able to stand, and my mind is whirling,',
  '1.31': 'And I see adverse omens, O Keśava. Nor do I foresee any advantage from slaying kinsmen in battle.',
  '1.32': 'For I desire not victory, O Kṛṣṇa, nor kingdom, nor pleasures; what is kingdom to us, O Govinda, what enjoyment, or even life?',
  '1.33': 'Those for whose sake we desire kingdom, enjoyments and pleasures, they stand here in battle, abandoning life and riches—',
  '1.34': 'Teachers, fathers, sons, as well as grandfathers, uncles, fathers-in-law, grandsons, brothers-in-law, and other relatives.',
  '1.35': 'These I do not wish to kill, though myself slain, O Madhusūdana, even for the sake of the kingdom of the three worlds; how then for earth?',
  '1.36': 'Slaying these sons of Dhṛtarāṣṭra, what pleasure can be ours, O Janārdana? Killing these felons we shall but incur sin.',
  '1.37': 'Therefore we should not kill the sons of Dhṛtarāṣṭra, our relatives; for how, killing our kinsmen, may we be happy, O Mādhava?',
  '1.38': 'Although these, with understanding overpowered by greed, see no guilt in the destruction of a family, no crime in hostility to friends,',
  '1.39': 'Why should not we, who clearly see the guilt in the destruction of a family, learn to turn away from this sin, O Janārdana?',
  '1.40': 'In the destruction of a family the immemorial family traditions perish; in the perishing of traditions, lawlessness overcomes the whole family.',
  '1.41': 'Owing to predominance of lawlessness, O Kṛṣṇa, the women of the family become corrupt; women corrupted, O Vārṣṇeya, there ariseth caste-confusion.',
  '1.42': 'This confusion draggeth to hell the slayers of the family and the family itself; the ancestors indeed fall, deprived of rice-balls and libations.',
  '1.43': 'By these caste-confusing misdeeds of the slayers of the family the everlasting caste-customs and family-customs are blotted out.',
  '1.44': 'The dwelling in hell, O Janārdana, is decreed for those men whose family-customs are blotted out — thus have we heard.',
  '1.45': 'Alas! in committing a great sin are we engaged, we who are endeavouring to kill our kindred, from greed of the pleasures of kingdom.',
  '1.46': 'If the sons of Dhṛtarāṣṭra, weapons in hand, should slay me, unresisting, unarmed, in the battle, that would be better for me.',
  '1.47': 'Sañjaya said: Having thus spoken on the battlefield, Arjuna sank down in the chariot, casting away his bow and arrow, his mind overborne with grief.',

  // ── Chapter 2 ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  '2.1': 'Sañjaya said: Unto him thus by pity overcome, with eyes tearful and downcast, sorrowing, Madhusūdana spake these words:',
  '2.2': 'The Blessed Lord said: Whence cometh upon thee this dejection, ignoble, heaven-barring, disgraceful, O Arjuna?',
  '2.6': 'Nor do we know which for us be the better, that we conquer them or they conquer us; these, whom having slain we should not care to live, even these stand before us, the sons of Dhṛtarāṣṭra.',
  '2.7': 'My very being is stricken with the weakness of sentimental pity. With mind bewildered about duty, I ask Thee. Tell me decisively what is good for me. I am Thy disciple, suppliant to Thee; teach me.',
  '2.8': 'For I see not what shall drive away this anguish that drieth up my senses, even should I attain rich and unrivalled kingdom on earth, or sovereignty over the gods.',
  '2.9': 'Sañjaya said: Having thus addressed Hṛṣīkeśa, Guḍākeśa, conqueror of his foes, said unto Govinda, "I will not fight," and became silent.',
  '2.10': 'Him, thus despondent, between the two armies, O Bhārata, Hṛṣīkeśa, smiling as it were, addressed in these words:',
  '2.11': 'The Blessed Lord said: Thou hast grieved for those that should not be grieved for, yet thou speakest words of wisdom. The wise grieve neither for the living nor for the dead.',
  '2.12': 'Nor at any time verily was I not, nor thou, nor these princes of men, nor verily shall we ever cease to be, hereafter.',
  '2.15': 'The man whom these afflict not, O chief of men, balanced in pain and pleasure, steadfast, he is fitted for immortality.',
  '2.16': 'The unreal hath no being; the real never ceaseth to be; the truth about both hath been seen by the seers of the Essence of things.',
  '2.17': 'Know That to be indestructible by whom all this is pervaded. Nor can any work the destruction of that imperishable One.',
  '2.18': 'These bodies of the embodied One, who is eternal, indestructible and boundless, are known as finite. Therefore fight, O Bhārata.',
  '2.19': 'He who regardeth this as a slayer, and he who thinketh he is slain, both of them are ignorant. He slayeth not, nor is he slain.',
  '2.20': 'He is not born, nor doth he die; nor having been, ceaseth he any more to be; unborn, perpetual, eternal and ancient, he is not slain when the body is slaughtered.',
  '2.21': 'Who knoweth him indestructible, perpetual, unborn, undiminishing, how can that man slay, O Pārtha, or cause to be slain?',
  '2.24': 'He cannot be cleft, nor can he be burnt, nor can he be wetted, nor yet can he be dried; perpetual, all-pervasive, stable, immovable, ancient,',
  '2.25': 'Unmanifest, unthinkable, immutable, he is called; therefore knowing him as such, thou shouldst not grieve.',
  '2.26': 'Or if thou thinkest of him as being constantly born and constantly dying, even then, O mighty-armed, thou shouldst not grieve.',
  '2.27': 'For certain is death for the born, and certain is birth for the dead; therefore over the inevitable thou shouldst not grieve.',
  '2.28': 'Beings are unmanifest in their origin, manifest in their midmost state, O Bhārata, unmanifest likewise are they in dissolution. What room then for lamentation?',
  '2.29': 'As a marvel one beholdeth Him, and as a marvel another speaketh thereof, and as a marvel another heareth thereof; yet having heard, none indeed knoweth Him.',
  '2.30': 'This dweller in the body of every one is ever invulnerable, O Bhārata; therefore thou shouldst not grieve for any creature.',
  '2.31': 'Further, looking to thine own duty thou shouldst not tremble; for there is nothing more welcome to a Kṣattriya than righteous war.',
  '2.32': 'Happy the Kṣattriyas, O Pārtha, who obtain such a fight, offered unsought as an open door to heaven.',
  '2.33': 'But if thou wilt not carry on this righteous warfare, then casting away thine own duty and thine honour, thou wilt incur sin.',
  '2.34': 'Men will recount thy perpetual dishonour, and to one highly esteemed dishonour exceedeth death.',
  '2.35': 'The great chariot-warriors will think thee fled from the battle through fear; and thou, that wast highly thought of by them, wilt be lightly held.',
  '2.36': 'Many unseemly words will be spoken by thine enemies, slandering thy strength; what is more painful than that?',
  '2.37': 'Slain, thou wilt obtain heaven; victorious, thou wilt enjoy the earth; therefore stand up, O son of Kuntī, resolute to fight.',
  '2.38': 'Taking as equal pleasure and pain, gain and loss, victory and defeat, gird thee for the battle; thus thou shalt not incur sin.',
  '2.39': 'This which hath been declared unto thee is the wisdom of Sāṅkhya; hear now the wisdom of Yoga, joined whereunto, O Pārtha, thou shalt cast off the bonds of action.',
  '2.40': 'In this there is no waste of effort, nor is there any production of contrary results; even a little of this knowledge protects from great fear.',
  '2.41': 'The determinate Reason is but one-pointed, O joy of the Kurus; many-branched and endless are the thoughts of the irresolute.',
  '2.42': 'The unwise, delighting in the letter of the Veda, declare that there is naught else, O Pārtha, full of desires, having heaven for their goal,',
  '2.43': 'Offering rebirth as the fruit of action, prescribing manifold rites of various kinds for the obtaining of pleasure and lordship.',
  '2.44': 'For them, attached to pleasure and lordship, with thought stolen away by such teaching, no determinate Reason is engendered, fixed in concentration.',
  '2.45': 'The Vedas deal with the three attributes; be thou above the three attributes, O Arjuna; beyond the pairs of opposites, ever steadfast in purity, careless of possessions, full of the Self.',
  '2.46': 'All the Vedas are as useful to an enlightened Brāhmaṇa as is a tank in a place covered all over with water.',
  '2.49': 'Far lower than the Yoga of Discrimination is action, O Dhanañjaya. Take thou refuge in the Pure Reason; pitiable are they who work for fruit.',
  '2.51': 'The Sages, united to the Pure Reason, renouncing the fruit which action yieldeth, liberated from the bonds of birth, go to the blissful seat.',
  '2.52': 'When thy mind shall escape from this tangle of delusion, then thou shalt rise to indifference as to what hath been heard and shall be heard.',
  '2.53': 'When thy mind, bewildered by the Śruti, shall stand immovable, fixed in contemplation, then shalt thou attain unto Yoga.',
  '2.54': 'Arjuna said: What is the mark of him who is stable of mind, steadfast in contemplation, O Keśava? How doth the stable-minded talk, how doth he sit, how walk?',
  '2.55': 'The Blessed Lord said: When a man abandoneth, O Pārtha, all the desires of the heart, and is satisfied in the Self by the Self, then is he called stable in mind.',
  '2.56': 'He whose mind is free from anxiety amid pains, indifferent amid pleasures, loosed from passion, fear and anger, he is called a sage of stable mind.',
  '2.57': 'He who on every side is without attachments, whatever hap of fair and foul, who neither likes nor dislikes, of such a one the understanding is well-poised.',
  '2.58': 'When, again, as a tortoise draws in on all sides its limbs, he withdraws his senses from the objects of sense, then is his understanding well-poised.',
  '2.59': 'The objects of sense, but not the relish for them, turn away from an abstemious dweller in the body; and even relish turneth away from him after the Supreme is seen.',
  '2.60': 'O son of Kuntī, the excited senses of even a wise man, though he be striving, impetuously carry away his mind.',
  '2.61': 'Having restrained them all, he should sit harmonised, I his supreme goal; for whose senses are mastered, of him the understanding is well-poised.',
  '2.64': 'But the disciplined self, moving among sense-objects with senses free from attraction and repulsion, mastered by the Self, goeth to Peace.',
  '2.65': 'In that Peace the extinction of all pains ariseth for him; for of him whose heart is peaceful the Reason soon attaineth equilibrium.',
  '2.66': 'There is no pure Reason for the non-harmonised, nor for the non-harmonised is there concentration; for him without concentration there is no peace, and for the unpeaceful, how can there be happiness?',
  '2.67': 'Such of the roving senses as the mind yieldeth to, that hurries away the understanding, just as the gale hurries away a ship upon the waters.',
  '2.68': 'Therefore, O mighty-armed, whose senses are all withdrawn from the objects of sense, of him the understanding is well-poised.',
  '2.69': 'That which is the night of all beings, for the disciplined man is the time of waking; when other beings are waking, then is it night for the Muni who seeth.',
  '2.70': 'He attaineth Peace, into whom all desires flow as rivers flow into the ocean, which is filled with water but remaineth unmoved — not he who desireth desires.',
  '2.71': 'Whoso forsaketh all desires and goeth onwards free from yearnings, selfless and without egoism — he goeth to Peace.',
  '2.72': 'This is the Eternal state, O son of Pṛthā. Having attained thereto none is bewildered. Who, even at the death-hour, is established therein, he goeth to the Nirvāṇa of the Eternal.',

  // ── Chapter 3 ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  '3.1': 'If it be thought by Thee that knowledge is superior to action, O Janardana, why dost Thou, O Keshava, enjoin on me this terrible action?',
  '3.2': 'With these perplexing words Thou only confusest my understanding; therefore tell me with certainty the one way by which I may attain bliss.',
  '3.3': 'The Blessed Lord said: In this world a twofold path was given by Me at first, O sinless one — that of Yoga by knowledge for the Sankhyas, and that of Yoga by action for the Yogins.',
  '3.4': 'Not by abstention from works does a man attain to actionlessness, nor by mere renunciation does he rise to perfection.',
  '3.5': 'Nor can anyone, even for an instant, remain really actionless; for helplessly is everyone driven to action by the qualities born of nature.',
  '3.6': 'Who sitteth, controlling the organs of action, but dwelling in his mind on the objects of the senses, that bewildered man is called a hypocrite.',
  '3.7': 'But who, controlling the senses by the mind, O Arjuna, with the organs of action without attachment performeth Yoga by action, he is worthy.',
  '3.8': 'Perform thou right action, for action is superior to inaction, and, inactive, even the maintenance of thy body would not be possible.',
  '3.9': 'The world is bound by action, save when this action is performed as sacrifice; for the sake of this, O son of Kunti, perform thou action, free from attachment.',
  '3.10': 'Having in ancient times emanated mankind together with sacrifice, the Lord of emanation said: "By this shall ye propagate; this shall be to you the cow of plenty."',
  '3.11': 'With this nourish ye the Shining Ones, and may the Shining Ones nourish you; thus, nourishing one another, ye shall reap the supremest good.',
  '3.12': 'For, nourished by sacrifice, the Shining Ones shall verily bestow on you the desired enjoyments. A thief verily is he who enjoyeth what is given by Them without returning Them aught.',
  '3.13': 'The righteous, who eat the remains of the sacrifice, are freed from all sins; but the impious, who dress food only for their own sakes, verily eat sin.',
  '3.14': 'From food creatures become; from rain is the production of food; rain proceedeth from sacrifice; sacrifice ariseth out of action;',
  '3.15': 'Know thou that from Brahman action groweth, and Brahman from the Imperishable cometh. Therefore the Brahman, the all-permeating, is ever present in sacrifice.',
  '3.16': 'He who on earth doth not follow the wheel thus revolving, sinful of life and rejoicing in the senses, he, O son of Pritha, liveth in vain.',
  '3.17': 'But the man who rejoiceth in the SELF, with the SELF is satisfied, and is content in the SELF — for him verily there is nothing to do.',
  '3.18': 'For him there is no interest in what is done or what is not done in this world; nor doth any object of his depend on any being.',
  '3.19': 'Therefore, without attachment, constantly perform action which is duty; for, performing action without attachment, man verily reacheth the Supreme.',
  '3.20': 'Verily by action Janaka and others attained perfection; then having an eye to the welfare of the world also, thou shouldst perform action.',
  '3.22': 'There is nothing in the three worlds, O Partha, that should be done by Me, nor anything unattained that might be attained; yet I mingle in action.',
  '3.23': 'For if I mingled not ever in action, unwearied, men all around would follow My path, O son of Pritha.',
  '3.24': 'These worlds would fall into ruin if I did not perform action; I should be the author of confusion of castes, and should destroy these creatures.',
  '3.25': 'As the ignorant act from attachment to action, O Bharata, so should the wise act without attachment, desiring the welfare of the world.',
  '3.26': 'Let no wise man unsettle the mind of ignorant people attached to action; he should engage them in all actions, himself performing them with devotion.',
  '3.27': 'All actions are wrought by the qualities of nature only. The self, deluded by egoism, thinketh: "I am the doer."',
  '3.28': 'But he, O mighty-armed, who knoweth the essence of the divisions of the qualities and functions, holding that "the qualities move amid the qualities," is not attached.',
  '3.29': 'Those deluded by the qualities of nature are attached to the functions of the qualities. The man of perfect knowledge should not unsettle the foolish whose knowledge is imperfect.',
  '3.30': 'Surrendering all actions to Me, with thy thoughts resting on the supreme SELF, from hope and egoism freed, and of mental fever cured, engage in battle.',
  '3.31': 'Who abide ever in this teaching of Mine, full of faith and free from cavilling, they too are released from actions.',
  '3.32': 'But those who, cavilling at My teaching, act not thereon, deluded in all knowledge, know thou these mindless ones as doomed to destruction.',
  '3.33': 'Even the man of knowledge behaveth in conformity with his own nature; beings follow nature; what shall restraint avail?',
  '3.34': 'Affection and aversion for the objects of sense abide in the senses; let none come under the dominion of these two; they are obstructors of the path.',
  '3.36': 'Arjuna said: But dragged on by what doth a man commit sin, reluctantly indeed, O Varshneya, as it were by force constrained?',
  '3.37': 'The Blessed Lord said: It is desire, it is wrath, begotten by the quality of mobility; all-consuming, all-polluting, know thou this as our foe here on earth.',
  '3.38': 'As a flame is enveloped by smoke, as a mirror by dust, as an embryo is wrapped by the amnion, so This is enveloped by it.',
  '3.39': 'Enveloped is wisdom, O son of Kunti, by this constant enemy of the wise, in the form of desire, which is insatiable as a flame.',
  '3.40': 'The senses, the mind and the Reason are said to be its seat; by these enveloping wisdom, it bewildereth the dweller in the body.',
  '3.41': 'Therefore, O best of the Bharatas, mastering first the senses, do thou slay this thing of sin, destructive of wisdom and knowledge.',
  '3.42': 'It is said that the senses are great; greater than the senses is the mind; greater than the mind is the Reason; but what is greater than the Reason, is HE.',
  '3.43': 'Thus understanding Him as greater than the Reason, restraining the self by the SELF, slay thou, O mighty-armed, the enemy in the form of desire, difficult to overcome.',

  // ── Chapter 4 ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  '4.1': 'The Blessed Lord said: This imperishable Yoga I declared to Vivasvan; Vivasvan taught it to Manu; Manu to Ikshvaku told it.',
  '4.2': 'This, handed on down the line, the King-Sages knew. This Yoga, by great efflux of time, decayed in the world, O Parantapa.',
  '4.3': 'This same ancient Yoga hath been to-day declared to thee by Me, for thou art My devotee and My friend; it is the supreme Secret.',
  '4.4': 'Arjuna said: Later was Thy birth, earlier the birth of Vivasvan; how then am I to understand that Thou declaredst it in the beginning?',
  '4.5': 'The Blessed Lord said: Many births have been left behind by Me and by thee, O Arjuna. I know them all, but thou knowest not thine, O Parantapa.',
  '4.6': 'Though unborn, the imperishable SELF, and also the Lord of all beings, brooding over nature, which is Mine own, yet I am born through My own Power.',
  '4.9': 'He who thus knoweth My divine birth and action, in essence, having abandoned the body cometh not to birth again, but cometh unto Me, O Arjuna.',
  '4.10': 'Freed from passion, fear and anger, filled with Me, taking refuge in Me, purified in the fire of wisdom, many have entered into My Being.',
  '4.11': 'However men approach Me, even so do I welcome them, for the path men take from every side is Mine, O Partha.',
  '4.12': 'They who long after success in action on earth sacrifice to the Shining Ones; for in brief space verily, in this world of men, success is born of action.',
  '4.13': 'The four castes were emanated by Me, by the different distribution of qualities and actions; know Me to be the author of them, though the actionless and inexhaustible.',
  '4.14': 'Nor do actions affect Me, nor is the fruit of action desired by Me. He who thus knoweth Me is not bound by actions.',
  '4.15': 'Having thus known, our forefathers, ever seeking liberation, performed action; therefore do thou also perform action, as did our forefathers in the olden time.',
  '4.16': 'What is action, what inaction? — even sages are herein perplexed. It is needful therefore to discriminate action; I will declare to thee that action by knowing which thou shalt be loosed from evil.',
  '4.17': 'It is needful to discriminate action, to discriminate unlawful action, and to discriminate inaction; mysterious is the path of action.',
  '4.18': 'He who seeth inaction in action, and action in inaction, he is wise among men, he is harmonious, even while performing all action.',
  '4.19': 'Whose works are all free from the moulding of desire, whose actions are burned up by the fire of wisdom, him the WISE have called a Sage.',
  '4.20': 'Having abandoned attachment to the fruit of action, always content, nowhere seeking refuge, he is not doing anything, although doing actions.',
  '4.21': 'Hoping for naught, his mind and self controlled, having relinquished all greed, performing action by the body alone, he doth not commit sin.',
  '4.22': 'Content with whatsoever cometh to him without effort of his own, passed beyond the pairs of opposites, free from envy, balanced in success and failure, though acting he is not bound.',
  '4.23': 'Of one with attachment dead, harmonious, with his thoughts established in wisdom, his works pure sacrifice, all action melts away.',
  '4.24': 'The BRAHMAN is the oblation; the BRAHMAN is the clarified butter; by the BRAHMAN is the oblation poured into the fire of the BRAHMAN; the BRAHMAN verily shall be reached by him who always seeth the BRAHMAN in action.',
  '4.25': 'Some Yogis offer up sacrifice to the Shining Ones alone; others sacrifice only by pouring the sacrifice into the fire of the eternal.',
  '4.26': 'Some pour as sacrifice hearing and the other senses into the fires of restraint; some pour as sacrifice sound and the other objects of sense into the fires of the senses.',
  '4.27': 'Others again pour as sacrifice all the functions of the senses and the functions of life into the wisdom-kindled fire of union with the SELF.',
  '4.28': 'Yet others the sacrifice of wealth, the sacrifice of austerity, the sacrifice of Yoga, the sacrifice of silent reading and wisdom, men of disciplined vows.',
  '4.29': 'Yet others, devoted to breath-control, having restrained the paths of prana and apana, pour as sacrifice prana into apana and apana into prana.',
  '4.30': 'Others, regular in food, pour as sacrifice their life-breaths into life-breaths. All these know what sacrifice is, and have their sins consumed by sacrifice.',
  '4.31': 'They who enjoy the life-giving remains of sacrifice go to the eternal BRAHMAN. This world is not for the non-sacrificer; how then any other, O best of the Kurus?',
  '4.32': 'Many and various sacrifices are thus spread out before the BRAHMAN. Know thou that all these are born of action, and thus knowing thou shalt be free.',
  '4.33': 'Better than the sacrifice of any objects is the sacrifice of wisdom, O Parantapa. All actions in their entirety, O Partha, culminate in wisdom.',
  '4.34': 'Learn thou this by discipleship, by investigation, and by service. The wise, the seers of the Essence of things, will instruct thee in wisdom.',
  '4.35': 'Having known this, thou shalt not again, O Pandava, thus fall into error; and by this thou shalt see all beings without exception in the SELF, and thus in Me.',
  '4.36': 'Even shouldst thou be the most sinful of all sinners, yet shalt thou cross over all sin by the bark of wisdom.',
  '4.37': 'As the burning fire reduceth fuel to ashes, O Arjuna, so doth the wisdom-fire reduce all actions to ashes.',
  '4.38': 'Verily there is no purifier in this world like wisdom; he that is perfected in Yoga finds it in the SELF in due season.',
  '4.39': 'The man who is full of faith obtaineth wisdom, and he also who hath mastery over his senses; and having obtained wisdom, swiftly he goeth to the supreme Peace.',
  '4.40': 'But the ignorant, faithless, doubting self goeth to destruction; nor this world, nor that beyond, nor happiness, is there for the doubting self.',
  '4.41': 'He who hath renounced actions by Yoga, who hath cloven asunder doubt by wisdom, who is ruled by the SELF, actions do not bind him, O Dhananjaya.',
  '4.42': 'Therefore, with the sword of the wisdom of the SELF cleaving asunder this ignorance-born doubt, dwelling in the heart, be established in Yoga. Stand up, O Bharata.',

  // ── Chapter 5 ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  '5.1': 'Arjuna said: Renunciation of actions Thou praisest, O Krishna, and then also Yoga; of the two, which one is the better? That tell me conclusively.',
  '5.2': 'The Blessed Lord said: Renunciation and Yoga by action both lead to the highest bliss; of the two, Yoga by action is verily better than renunciation of action.',
  '5.3': 'He should be known as a perpetual ascetic, who neither hateth nor desireth; free from the pairs of opposites, O mighty-armed, happily he is freed from bondage.',
  '5.4': 'Children, not sages, speak of the Sankhya and the Yoga as different; he who is duly established in one obtaineth the fruits of both.',
  '5.5': 'That place which is gained by the Sankhyas is reached by the Yogis also. He seeth, who seeth that the Sankhya and the Yoga are one.',
  '5.6': 'But renunciation, O mighty-armed, is difficult to attain without Yoga; the Yoga-harmonised Sage swiftly goeth to the BRAHMAN.',
  '5.7': 'He who is harmonised by Yoga, the self-purified, Self-ruled, the senses subdued, whose Self is the SELF of all beings, although acting he is not affected.',
  '5.8': '"I am not doing anything," so the harmonised knower of the Essence thinketh, seeing, hearing, touching, smelling, eating, going, sleeping, breathing,',
  '5.9': 'Speaking, letting go, holding, opening and closing the eyes; he holdeth: "the senses move among the objects of the senses."',
  '5.10': 'He who acteth, placing all actions in the BRAHMAN, abandoning attachment, is unaffected by sin as a lotus-leaf by the waters.',
  '5.11': 'Yogis, having abandoned attachment, perform actions only by the body, by the mind, by the Reason, and even by the senses, for the purification of the self.',
  '5.12': 'The harmonised man, having abandoned the fruit of action, attaineth to the eternal Peace; the non-harmonised, impelled by desire, attached to fruit, are bound.',
  '5.13': 'Mentally renouncing all actions, the sovereign dweller in the body resteth serenely in the nine-gated city, neither acting nor causing to act.',
  '5.14': 'The Lord of the world produceth neither the idea of agency, nor actions, nor the union together of action and its fruit; nature, however, manifesteth.',
  '5.15': 'The Lord accepteth neither the evil-doing nor yet the well-doing of any. Wisdom is enveloped by unwisdom; therewith mortals are deluded.',
  '5.16': 'Verily, in whom unwisdom is destroyed by the wisdom of the SELF, in them wisdom, shining as the sun, revealeth the Supreme.',
  '5.17': 'Thinking on THAT, merged in THAT, established in THAT, solely devoted to THAT, they go whence there is no return, their sins dispelled by wisdom.',
  '5.18': 'Sages look equally on a Brahmana adorned with learning and humility, a cow, an elephant, and even a dog, and an outcaste.',
  '5.19': 'Even here on earth the Heaven-world is conquered by those whose mind resteth in equilibrium; the BRAHMAN is incorruptible and equilibrated; therefore they are established in the BRAHMAN.',
  '5.20': 'With Reason firm, unperplexed, the knower of the BRAHMAN, established in the BRAHMAN, neither rejoiceth on obtaining what is pleasant, nor sorroweth on obtaining what is unpleasant.',
  '5.21': 'He whose self is unattached to external contacts, and findeth joy in the SELF, having the self harmonised with the BRAHMAN by Yoga, enjoyeth happiness exempt from decay.',
  '5.22': 'The delights that are contact-born, they are verily wombs of pain, for they have beginning and ending, O Kaunteya; not in them may rejoice the wise.',
  '5.23': 'He who is able to endure here on earth, ere he be liberated from the body, the force born from desire and passion, he is harmonised, he is a happy man.',
  '5.24': 'He who is happy within, who rejoiceth within, who is illuminated within, that Yogi, becoming the BRAHMAN, goeth to the Peace of the BRAHMAN.',
  '5.25': 'Rishis, their sins destroyed, their duality removed, their selves controlled, intent upon the welfare of all beings, obtain the Peace of the BRAHMAN.',
  '5.26': 'The Peace of the BRAHMAN lieth near to those who know themselves, who are disjoined from desire and passion, subdued in nature, of subdued thoughts.',
  '5.27': 'Having external contacts excluded, and with gaze fixed between the eyebrows; having made equal the outgoing and incoming breaths moving within the nostrils,',
  '5.28': 'With senses, mind and Reason ever controlled, solely pursuing liberation, the Sage, having for ever cast away desire, fear and passion, verily is liberated.',
  '5.29': 'Having known Me, as the Enjoyer of sacrifice and of austerity, the mighty Lord of all the worlds, the Friend of all beings, he goeth to Peace.',

  // ── Chapter 6 ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  '6.1': 'The Blessed Lord said: He that performeth such action as is duty, independently of the fruit of action, he is an ascetic, he is a yogi, not he that is without fire and without rites.',
  '6.2': 'That which is called renunciation know thou that as yoga, O Pāṇḍava; nor doth any one become a yogi with the formative will unrenounced.',
  '6.3': 'For a sage who is seeking yoga, action is called the means; for the same sage, when he is enthroned in yoga, serenity is called the means.',
  '6.4': 'When a man feeleth no attachment either for the objects of sense or for actions, renouncing the formative will, then, he is said to be enthroned in yoga.',
  '6.7': 'The higher Self of him who is self-governed and peaceful is balanced in cold and heat, pleasure and pain, as also in honour and dishonour.',
  '6.8': 'The yogi who is satisfied with wisdom and knowledge, unwavering, master of his senses, to whom a lump of earth, a stone and gold are the same, is said to be harmonised.',
  '6.9': 'He who regardeth impartially lovers, friends, and foes, strangers, neutrals, foreigners and relatives, also the righteous and unrighteous, he excelleth.',
  '6.10': 'Let the yogi constantly engage himself in yoga, remaining in a secret place by himself, with thought and self subdued, free from hope and greed.',
  '6.11': 'In a pure place, established on a fixed seat of his own, neither very much raised nor very low, made of a cloth, a black antelope skin, and kuśa grass, one over the other,',
  '6.12': 'There, having made the mind one-pointed, with thought and the functions of the senses subdued, steady on his seat, he should practise yoga for the purification of the self.',
  '6.13': 'Holding the body, head and neck erect, immovably steady, looking fixedly at the point of the nose, with unseeing gaze,',
  '6.14': 'The self serene, fearless, firm in the vow of the Brahmachārī, the mind controlled, thinking on Me, harmonised, let him sit aspiring after Me.',
  '6.15': 'The yogi, ever united thus with the Self, with the mind controlled, goeth to peace, to the supreme bliss that abideth in Me.',
  '6.16': 'Verily yoga is not for him who eateth too much, nor who abstaineth to excess, nor who is too much addicted to sleep, nor even to wakefulness, O Arjuna.',
  '6.17': 'Yoga killeth out all pain for him who is regulated in eating and amusement, regulated in performing actions, regulated in sleeping and waking.',
  '6.18': 'When his subdued thought is fixed on the Self, free from longing after all desirable things, then it is said, "He is harmonised."',
  '6.19': 'As a lamp in a windless place flickereth not, to such is likened the yogi of subdued thought, absorbed in the yoga of the Self.',
  '6.20': 'That in which the mind, made restful by the practice of yoga, ceaseth, that in which, beholding the Self by the Self, in the Self he is content;',
  '6.21': 'That in which he findeth the supreme delight which the Reason can grasp beyond the senses, wherein established, he moveth not from the Reality;',
  '6.22': 'Which, having obtained, he thinketh there is no greater gain beyond it; wherein established, he is not shaken even by heavy sorrow;',
  '6.23': 'That should be known by the name of yoga, this disconnection from the union with pain. This yoga must be clung to with a firm conviction and with undesponding mind.',
  '6.24': 'Abandoning without reserve all desires born of the imagination, by the mind curbing in the aggregate of the senses on every side,',
  '6.25': 'Little by little let him gain tranquillity by means of Reason controlled by steadiness; having made the mind abide in the Self, let him not think of anything.',
  '6.26': 'As often as the wavering and unsteady mind goeth forth, so often reining it in, let him bring it under the control of the Self.',
  '6.27': 'Supreme joy is for this yogi whose mind is peaceful, whose passion-nature is calmed, who is sinless and of the nature of the Eternal.',
  '6.28': 'The yogi who, thus ever harmonising the self, hath put away sin, he easily enjoyeth the infinite bliss of contact with the Eternal.',
  '6.29': 'The self, harmonised by yoga, seeth the Self abiding in all beings, all beings in the Self; everywhere he seeth the same.',
  '6.31': 'He who, established in unity, worshippeth Me, abiding in all beings, that yogi liveth in Me, whatever his mode of living.',
  '6.32': 'He who, through the likeness of the Self, O Arjuna, seeth equality in everything, whether pleasant or painful, he is considered a perfect yogi.',
  '6.33': 'Arjuna said: This yoga which Thou hast declared to be by equanimity, O Madhusūdana, I see not a stable foundation for it, owing to restlessness.',
  '6.35': 'The Blessed Lord said: Without doubt, O mighty-armed, the mind is hard to curb and restless; but it may be curbed by constant practice and by dispassion.',
  '6.36': 'Yoga is hard to attain, methinks, by a self that is uncontrolled; but by the self-controlled it is attainable by properly directed energy.',
  '6.37': 'Arjuna said: He who is unsubdued but who possesseth faith, with the mind wandering away from yoga, failing to attain perfection in yoga, what path doth he tread, O Kṛṣṇa?',
  '6.38': 'Fallen from both, is he destroyed like a rent cloud, unsteadfast, O mighty-armed, deluded in the path of the Eternal?',
  '6.39': 'Deign, O Kṛṣṇa, to completely dispel this doubt of mine; for there is none to be found save Thyself able to destroy this doubt.',
  '6.40': 'The Blessed Lord said: O son of Pṛthā, neither in this world nor in the life to come is there destruction for him; never doth any who worketh righteousness, O beloved, tread the path of woe.',
  '6.41': 'Having attained to the worlds of the pure-doing, and having dwelt there for eternal years, he who fell from yoga is reborn in a pure and blessed house;',
  '6.42': 'Or he may even be born into a family of wise yogis; but such a birth as that is most difficult to obtain in this world.',
  '6.43': 'There he recovereth the characteristics belonging to his former body, and with these he again laboureth for perfection, O joy of the Kurus.',
  '6.44': 'By that former practice he is borne on irresistibly. Even the enquirer after yoga goeth beyond the Brahmic word.',
  '6.45': 'But the yogi, labouring with assiduity, purified from sin, fully perfected through manifold births, he reacheth the supreme goal.',
  '6.46': 'The yogi is greater than the ascetics; he is thought to be greater even than the wise; the yogi is greater than the men of action; therefore become thou a yogi, O Arjuna.',
  '6.47': 'And among all yogis, he who, full of faith, with the inner self abiding in Me, adoreth Me, he is considered by Me to be the most completely harmonised.',

  // ── Chapter 7 ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  '7.1': 'The Blessed Lord said: With the mind clinging to Me, O Pārtha, performing yoga, taking refuge in Me, how thou shalt without doubt know Me to the uttermost, that hear thou.',
  '7.2': 'I will declare to thee this knowledge and wisdom in its completeness, which, having known, there is nothing more here needeth to be known.',
  '7.3': 'Among thousands of men scarce one striveth for perfection; of the successful strivers scarce one knoweth Me in essence.',
  '7.4': 'Earth, water, fire, air, ether, mind, Reason, and egoism — these are the eightfold division of My nature.',
  '7.5': 'This the inferior. Know My other nature, the higher, the life-element, O mighty-armed, by which the universe is upheld.',
  '7.6': 'Know this to be the womb of all beings. I am the source of the forthgoing of the whole universe and likewise the place of its dissolving.',
  '7.7': 'There is naught whatsoever higher than I, O Dhanañjaya. All this is threaded on Me, as rows of pearls on a string.',
  '7.8': 'I the sapidity in waters, O son of Kuntī, I the radiance in moon and sun; the Word of Power in all the Vedas, sound in ether, and virility in men;',
  '7.9': 'The pure fragrance of earths and the brilliance in fire am I; the life in all beings am I, and the austerity in ascetics.',
  '7.10': 'Know Me, O Pārtha, as the eternal seed of all beings; I am the Reason of the reason-endowed, the splendour of splendid things am I.',
  '7.11': 'Of the strong I am the strength, divorced from desire and passion. In beings I am desire not contrary to duty, O Lord of the Bhāratas.',
  '7.12': 'The natures that are harmonious, active, and slothful, that are indeed from Me; not I in them, but they in Me.',
  '7.13': 'All this world, deluded by these natures made by the three qualities, knoweth not Me above these, imperishable.',
  '7.14': 'This divine illusion of Mine, caused by the qualities, is hard to pierce; they who come to Me, they cross over this illusion.',
  '7.15': 'The evil-doing, the deluded, the vilest men, they come not to Me, they whose wisdom is destroyed by illusion, who have embraced the nature of demons.',
  '7.16': 'Fourfold in division are the righteous ones who worship Me, O Arjuna: the suffering, the seeker for knowledge, the self-interested, and the wise, O Lord of the Bhāratas.',
  '7.17': 'Of these the wise, ever harmonised, worshipping the One, is the best; for supremely dear am I to the wise, and he is dear to Me.',
  '7.18': 'Noble are all these, but I hold the wise as verily Myself; he, self-united, is fixed on Me, the highest path.',
  '7.19': 'At the close of many births the man full of wisdom cometh unto Me; "Vāsudeva is all," saith he, the Mahātmā, very difficult to find.',
  '7.20': 'They whose wisdom hath been rent away by desires manifold, betake themselves to other shining ones, holding to various rites, constrained by their own natures.',
  '7.21': 'Any devotee who seeketh to worship with faith any such aspect, I verily bestow the unswerving faith of that man.',
  '7.22': 'He, endowed with that faith, seeketh the worship of such a one, and from him he obtaineth his desires, I verily decreeing the benefits.',
  '7.23': 'Finite indeed the fruit; that belongeth to those of small intelligence. To the shining ones go the worshippers of the shining ones, but My devotees come unto Me.',
  '7.24': 'Those devoid of intelligence think of Me, the Unmanifest, as having manifestation, knowing not My supreme nature, imperishable, most excellent.',
  '7.25': 'Nor am I of all discovered, being veiled by the illusion of Yoga. This deluded world knoweth Me not, the unborn, the imperishable.',
  '7.26': 'I know the beings that are past, that are present, O Arjuna, and that are to come; but no one knoweth Me.',
  '7.27': 'By the delusion of the pairs of opposites, sprung from attraction and repulsion, O Bhārata, all beings walk this universe wholly deluded, O scorcher of foes.',
  '7.28': 'But men of pure deeds, in whom sin is come to an end, they, freed from the delusion of the pairs of opposites, worship Me, steadfast in vows.',
  '7.29': 'They who, taking refuge in Me, strive for liberation from birth and death, they know the Eternal, the whole Self-Knowledge, and all Action entire.',
  '7.30': 'They who know Me as the Knowledge of the Elements, of the Shining Ones, and of the Sacrifice, they, harmonised in mind, know Me verily even in the time of forthgoing.',

  // ── Chapter 8 ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  '8.1': 'Arjuna said: What is that Eternal, what Self-Knowledge, what Action, O Puruṣottama? And what is declared to be the Knowledge of the Elements, what is called the Knowledge of the Shining Ones?',
  '8.2': 'What is the Knowledge of Sacrifice in this body, and how, O Madhusūdana? And how at the time of forthgoing art Thou known by the self-controlled?',
  '8.3': 'The Blessed Lord said: The indestructible, the supreme is the Eternal; His essential nature is called Self-Knowledge; the emanation that causeth the birth of beings is named Action;',
  '8.4': 'Knowledge of the Elements concerns My perishable nature, and the Knowledge of the Shining Ones concerns the life-giving energy; the Knowledge of Sacrifice is Myself in this body, O best of the embodied.',
  '8.5': 'And whoso, casting off the body, goeth forth thinking upon Me only at the time of the end, he entereth into My being: there is no doubt of that.',
  '8.6': 'Whoso, at the end, abandoneth the body, thinking upon any being, to that being only he goeth, O Kaunteya, ever to that conformed in nature.',
  '8.7': 'Therefore at all times think upon Me only, and fight. With mind and Reason set on Me, without doubt thou shalt come to Me.',
  '8.8': 'With the mind not wandering after aught else, harmonised by continual practice, constantly meditating, O Pārtha, one goeth to the Spirit, supreme, divine.',
  '8.9': 'He who meditateth on the Ancient, the Seer, the Ruler, smaller than the small, yet the supporter of all, of inconceivable form, refulgent as the sun beyond the darkness;',
  '8.10': 'In the time of forthgoing, with unshaken mind, fixed in devotion, by the power of yoga drawing together his life-breath in the centre of the two eyebrows, he goeth to this Spirit, supreme, divine.',
  '8.11': 'That which is declared indestructible by the Veda-knowers, that which the controlled and passion-free enter, that desiring which Brahmacharya is performed, that path I will declare to thee with brevity.',
  '8.12': 'All the gates closed, the mind confined in the heart, the life-breath fixed in his own head, concentrated by yoga,',
  '8.13': '"Aum!" the one-syllabled Eternal, reciting, thinking upon Me, he who goeth forth, abandoning the body, he goeth on the highest path.',
  '8.14': 'He who constantly thinketh upon Me, not thinking ever of another, of him I am easily reached, O Pārtha, of this ever-harmonised yogi.',
  '8.15': 'Having come to Me, these Mahātmās come not again to birth, the place of pain, non-eternal; they have gone to the highest bliss.',
  '8.16': 'The worlds, beginning with the world of Brahmā, roll on, returning, O Arjuna; but he who cometh unto Me, O Kaunteya, hath no rebirth.',
  '8.17': 'They who know the day of Brahmā, a thousand ages in duration, and the night, a thousand ages in ending, they, men, know day and night.',
  '8.18': 'From the unmanifested all the manifested stream forth at the coming of day; at the coming of night they dissolve, even in That, called the unmanifested.',
  '8.19': 'This same multitude of beings, going forth repeatedly, is dissolved at the coming of night; by ordination, O Pārtha, it streameth forth at the coming of day.',
  '8.20': 'Therefore verily there existeth, higher than that unmanifested, another unmanifested eternal, which, in the destroying of all beings, is not destroyed.',
  '8.21': 'That unmanifested, "the Indestructible," it is called; it is spoken of as the highest Path. They who reach It return not. That is My supreme abode.',
  '8.22': 'He, the highest Spirit, O Pārtha, is reached by unswerving devotion to Him alone, in whom all beings abide, by whom all this is pervaded.',
  '8.23': 'The times in which yogis going forth return not, and also those in which going forth they return, those times shall I declare unto thee, O prince of the Bhāratas.',
  '8.24': 'Fire, light, daytime, the bright fortnight, the six months of the northern path — then, going forth, the men who know the Eternal go to the Eternal.',
  '8.25': 'Smoke, night-time, the dark fortnight also, the six months of the southern path — then the yogi, obtaining the lunar light, returneth.',
  '8.26': 'Light and darkness, these paths are thought to be eternal in the universe; by the one he goeth who returneth not, by the other he who returneth again.',
  '8.27': 'Knowing these paths, O Pārtha, no yogi is deluded; therefore in all times be firm in yoga, O Arjuna.',
  '8.28': 'Whatever fruit of pure deeds is assigned in the Vedas, in sacrifices, austerities and gifts also, beyond all these passeth the yogi, having known this; and he goeth to the supreme, primeval abode.',

  // ── Chapter 9 ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  '9.1': 'The Blessed Lord said: To thee, the uncavilling, verily shall I declare this profoundest Secret, wisdom combined with knowledge, which, having known, thou shalt be freed from evil.',
  '9.2': 'Royal Science, Royal Secret, supreme Purifier is this; intuitional, according to righteousness, very easy to perform, imperishable.',
  '9.3': 'Men without faith in this Law, O Parantapa, not reaching Me, return to the paths of the world of death.',
  '9.4': 'By Me all this world is pervaded, My form unmanifested; all beings have root in Me, I am not rooted in them.',
  '9.5': 'Nor have beings root in Me; behold My sovereign Yoga; I, the support of beings, yet not seated in beings, am Myself the cause of being.',
  '9.6': 'As the mighty wind, moving everywhere, ever resteth in the ākāsha, so all beings rest in Me; thus do thou comprehend.',
  '9.7': 'All beings, O Kaunteya, enter into My nature at the end of a kalpa; I emanate them again at the beginning of a kalpa.',
  '9.8': 'Taking hold of My own nature, I emanate again and again all this multitude of beings, helpless, by the force of nature.',
  '9.9': 'Nor do these works bind Me, O Dhanañjaya, enthroned on high, unattached to actions.',
  '9.10': 'Under Me as supervisor, nature sends forth the moving and the unmoving; because of this, O Kaunteya, the universe revolveth.',
  '9.11': 'The deluded disregard Me, clad in human semblance, ignorant of My supreme nature, the great Lord of beings.',
  '9.12': 'Empty of hope, empty of deeds, empty of wisdom, senseless, partaking of the deceitful, brutal and demoniacal nature.',
  '9.13': 'Verily the Mahātmās, O Pārtha, partaking of My divine nature, worship Me with unwavering mind, having known Me as the imperishable source of beings.',
  '9.14': 'Ever glorifying Me, strenuous, firm in vows, prostrating themselves before Me, they worship Me with devotion, ever harmonised.',
  '9.15': 'Others also, sacrificing with the wisdom-sacrifice, worship Me as the One and the Manifold everywhere present, facing in all directions.',
  '9.16': 'I the oblation; I the sacrifice; I the ancestral offering; I the fire-giving herb; the mantram I; I also the butter; I the fire; the burnt-offering I.',
  '9.17': 'I the Father of this universe, the Mother, the Supporter, the Grandsire, the Holy One to be known, the Word of Power, and also the Ṛik, the Sāman and the Yajus;',
  '9.18': 'The Way, the Supporter, the Lord, the Witness, the Abode, the Shelter, the Friend, the Origin, the Dissolution, the Foundation, the Treasure-house, the Seed imperishable.',
  '9.19': 'I give heat; I hold back and send forth the rain; immortality and also death, being and non-being am I, O Arjuna.',
  '9.20': 'The knowers of the three, drinkers of the soma-juice, their sins cleansed, worshipping Me with sacrifices, pray of Me the way to heaven; they, ascending to the holy world of the Ruler of the shining Ones, eat in heaven the divine feasts of the shining Ones.',
  '9.21': 'They, having enjoyed the spacious heaven-world, their merit exhausted, enter the world of mortals; thus following the virtues enjoined by the three, desiring desires, they obtain the changeable.',
  '9.23': 'Even the devotees of other shining Ones, who worship full of faith, even they, O Kaunteya, worship Me, though contrary to the ancient rule.',
  '9.24': 'I verily am the Enjoyer and Lord of all sacrifices; but they know Me not in essence, and hence they fall.',
  '9.25': 'Votaries of the shining Ones go to the shining Ones; to the Ancestors go the Ancestor-worshippers; to the Bhūtas go the Bhūta-worshippers; My worshippers come unto Me.',
  '9.26': 'He who offereth to Me with devotion a leaf, a flower, a fruit, water, that I accept from the striving self, offered as it is with devotion.',
  '9.28': 'Thus shalt thou be liberated from the bonds of actions, yielding good and evil fruits; thyself harmonised by the Yoga of renunciation, thou shalt come unto Me when set free.',
  '9.29': 'The same am I to all beings; there is none hateful to Me nor dear. They verily who worship Me with devotion, they are in Me, and I also in them.',
  '9.30': 'Even if the most sinful worship Me, with undivided heart, he too must be accounted righteous, for he hath rightly resolved;',
  '9.31': 'Speedily he becometh dutiful and goeth to eternal peace. O Kaunteya, know thou for certain that My devotee perisheth never.',
  '9.32': 'They who take refuge with Me, O Pārtha, though of the womb of sin, women, Vaishyas, even Shūdras, they also tread the highest Path.',
  '9.33': 'How much rather then holy Brāhmaṇas and devoted royal saints; having obtained this transient joyless world, worship thou Me.',
  '9.34': 'Merge thy mind in Me, be My devotee, sacrifice to Me, prostrate thyself before Me, harmonised thus in the Self, thou shalt come unto Me, having Me as thy supreme goal.',

  // ── Chapter 10 ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  '10.1': 'The Blessed Lord said: Further, O mighty-armed, hearken to My supreme word, that I, desirous of thy welfare, will declare to thee, beloved as thou art.',
  '10.2': 'Neither the hosts of the shining Ones, nor the great Ṛishis know My origin; for I am the beginning of the shining Ones and of the great Ṛishis, in every way.',
  '10.3': 'He who knoweth Me, unborn and beginningless, the great Lord of the worlds, he, undeluded among mortals, is liberated from all sins.',
  '10.4': 'Reason, knowledge, non-illusion, forgiveness, truth, self-control, calmness, pleasure, pain, birth, death, fear and also fearlessness,',
  '10.5': 'Harmlessness, equanimity, content, austerity, almsgiving, fame, obloquy, are the diverse natures of beings, that come forth from Me.',
  '10.6': 'The seven great Ṛishis, the ancient four, and also the Manus, partaking of My nature, were born from My mind, of whom are these creatures in the world.',
  '10.7': 'He who in essence knoweth this My divine manifestation and Yoga, he, by unfaltering Yoga, is united; there is no doubt thereof.',
  '10.8': 'I am the Source of all; from Me everything proceeds; with this conviction the wise worship Me, fixed in meditation.',
  '10.9': 'With Me in their thoughts, with their whole soul devoted to Me, enlightening one another, and ever conversing of Me, they are content and rejoice.',
  '10.10': 'To these, ever harmonious, worshipping Me with affection, I give the Yoga of discrimination, by which they come unto Me.',
  '10.11': 'Out of pure compassion for them, dwelling within their Self, I destroy the ignorance-born darkness by the shining lamp of wisdom.',
  '10.12': 'Arjuna said: Thou art the supreme Eternal, the supreme Abode, the supreme Purity, the eternal Divine Man, the Primal God, the Unborn, the Lord;',
  '10.13': 'All the Ṛishis declare this of Thee, as also the divine Ṛishi Nārada, Asita, Devala, Vyāsa, and Thou Thyself sayest it to me.',
  '10.14': 'All this I believe true that Thou sayest to me, O Keshava; verily, O Blessed Lord, neither the shining Ones nor the Dānavas comprehend Thy manifestation.',
  '10.15': 'Verily Thou Thyself knowest Thyself by Thyself, O Purushottama; Source of beings, Lord of beings, God of gods, Ruler of the world!',
  '10.16': 'Vouchsafe to declare without reserve Thy divine self-manifestations, by which manifestations Thou standest pervading these worlds.',
  '10.17': 'How may I know Thee, O Yogī, by constant meditation? In what various aspects art Thou, O Blessed Lord, to be thought of by me?',
  '10.18': 'Tell me again in detail, O Janārdana, of Thy Yoga and manifestations, for I am not satiated with hearing Thy life-giving words.',
  '10.19': 'The Blessed Lord said: Be it so! I will declare to thee My divine manifestations, but only those which are chief, O best of the Kurus, for there is no end to the detail of Me.',
  '10.20': 'I am the Self, O Gudākesha, seated in the heart of all beings; I am the beginning, the middle and also the end of all beings.',
  '10.21': 'Of the Ādityas I am Vishṇu; of luminaries the radiant Sun; I am Marīchi of the Maruts; of mansions of stars, the Moon.',
  '10.22': 'Of the Vedas I am the Sāma-veda; I am Vāsava of the shining Ones; and of the senses I am the Mind; and of living beings I am the intelligence.',
  '10.23': 'And of the Rudras I am Shankara; of the Yakshas and Rākshasas the Lord of Wealth; and of the Vasus I am Pāvaka; of mountains, Meru I am.',
  '10.24': 'And of household priests, O Pārtha, know Me chief, Bṛihaspati; of generals I am Skanda; of waters I am the Ocean.',
  '10.25': 'Of the great Ṛishis I am Bhṛigu; of words I am the one syllable AUM; of sacrifices I am the japa-sacrifice; of immovable things, the Himālaya.',
  '10.26': 'Of all trees Ashvattha, and of divine Ṛishis Nārada; of Gandharvas Chitraratha, of the perfected the Muni Kapila.',
  '10.27': 'Know Me, of horses, as Uchchaiḥshravas, ambrosia-born; of lordly elephants, Airāvata; and of men, the Monarch.',
  '10.28': 'Of weapons I am the thunderbolt; of cows I am Kāmadhuk; I am the progenitor Kandarpa; of serpents I am Vāsuki.',
  '10.29': 'And I am Ananta of the Nāgas; I am Varuṇa of aquatic beings; and Aryamā of the ancestors I am; I am Yama of governors.',
  '10.30': 'And I am Prahlāda of the Daityas; of calculators I am Time; and of beasts I am the Lord of beasts; and Vainateya of birds.',
  '10.31': 'Of purifiers I am the Wind; Rāma of warriors I am; of fishes I am Makara, and of streams the Gangā.',
  '10.32': 'Of creations the beginning and the end, and also the middle am I, O Arjuna; of sciences, the Science of the Self; the speech of orators I am.',
  '10.33': 'Of letters I am the letter A, and the dual of compounds; verily I am inexhaustible Time; I the Supporter, whose face turns everywhere.',
  '10.34': 'And I am all-devouring Death and the prosperity of those who shall be; of feminine qualities, fame, prosperity, speech, memory, intellect, constancy, forgiveness.',
  '10.35': 'Of hymns also, the Bṛihatsāman; of metres, Gāyatrī I; of months I am Mārgashīrsha, of seasons the flower-bearer.',
  '10.36': 'Of cheats I am the dice-play; the splendour of the splendid I; I am victory, I am determination, the truth of the truthful I.',
  '10.37': 'Of the Vṛishṇis I am Vāsudeva, of the Pāṇḍavas, Dhanañjaya; and of the Munis I am Vyāsa, of the Sages, Sage Ushanas.',
  '10.38': 'Of rulers I am the sceptre; of those that seek victory I am the statesmanship; and also of secrets I am silence; the wisdom of the wise I am.',
  '10.39': 'And whatsoever is the seed of all beings that am I, O Arjuna; nor is there aught, moving or unmoving, that may exist bereft of Me.',
  '10.40': 'There is no end of My divine manifestations, O Parantapa. This is only a brief declaration by Me of the extent of My manifestation.',
  '10.41': 'Whatsoever is glorious, beautiful and strong, understand thou that to go forth from a fragment of My splendour.',
  '10.42': 'But what is the knowledge of all these details to thee, O Arjuna? Having pervaded this whole universe with one fragment of Myself, I remain.',

  // ── Chapter 11 ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  '11.1': 'Arjuna said: As a grace to me Thou hast told the supreme Secret known as the Self; by Thy words my delusion is dispelled.',
  '11.2': 'The birth and dissolution of beings have been heard by me in detail from Thee, O lotus-eyed, and also Thy imperishable majesty.',
  '11.3': 'Thus it is, as Thou declarest Thyself, O Supreme Lord. I desire to see Thy Īshvara-Form, O Purushottama!',
  '11.4': 'If Thou thinkest that by me It can be seen, O Lord, Lord of Yoga, then show unto me Thy imperishable Self.',
  '11.5': 'The Blessed Lord said: Behold, O Pārtha, forms of Me, a hundredfold, a thousandfold, various in kind, divine, various in colours and shapes.',
  '11.6': 'Behold the Ādityas, Vasus, Rudras, the two Ashvins and Maruts also; behold many marvels never seen ere now, O Bhārata.',
  '11.7': 'Here, today, behold the whole universe, moving and unmoving, standing in one in My body, O Gudākesha, with aught else thou desirest to see.',
  '11.8': 'But verily thou art not able to behold Me with these thine eyes; the divine eye I give unto thee. Behold My sovereign Yoga.',
  '11.9': 'Sañjaya said: Having thus spoken, O King, the great Lord of Yoga, Hari, showed to Pārtha His supreme Īshvara-Form;',
  '11.10': 'With many mouths and eyes, with many wondrous sights, with many divine ornaments, with many uplifted divine weapons;',
  '11.11': 'Wearing divine garlands and vestures, anointed with divine unguents, the all-wonderful Resplendent One, endless, with face turned everywhere.',
  '11.12': 'If the splendour of a thousand suns were to blaze out at once in the sky, that would be like the splendour of that mighty Being.',
  '11.13': 'There Pāṇḍava beheld the whole universe, divided manifoldly, standing in one in the body of the God of gods.',
  '11.14': 'Then Dhanañjaya, overcome with astonishment, his hair upstanding, bowed down his head before the Shining One, and with joined palms spake.',
  '11.15': 'Arjuna said: I see all the gods, O God, within Thy body, and hosts of every kind of beings; Brahmā the Lord, seated on the lotus-throne, all the Ṛishis and divine Serpents.',
  '11.16': 'Many-bellied, many-mouthed, many-eyed, I behold Thee everywhere infinite in form; nor end nor middle nor beginning of Thee do I see, O Lord of all, Form universal.',
  '11.17': 'Diademed, club-bearing, discus-wielding, a mass of radiance flaming on every side, I behold Thee, hard to look upon, all around glowing as kindled fire and sun, immeasurable.',
  '11.18': 'Thou art the Imperishable, the Supreme to be known; Thou art the supreme support of this universe; Thou art the undying Guardian of the eternal Law; Thou art the ancient Purusha, I deem.',
  '11.19': 'Without beginning, middle or end, infinite in power, of infinite arms, the moon and sun Thy eyes, I behold Thee, Thy mouth a flaming fire, dazzling this universe with Thy radiance.',
  '11.20': 'By Thee alone is filled the space between earth and heaven and all the quarters; seeing this, Thy marvellous and awful Form, the three worlds tremble, O mighty-souled.',
  '11.21': 'Verily into Thee enter these hosts of Suras; some affrighted invoke Thee with joined palms; "May it be well!" saying, the bands of the great Ṛishis and the Siddhas hymn Thee with hymns excellent.',
  '11.22': 'The Rudras, Ādityas, Vasus, the Sādhyas, the Vishvas, the two Ashvins, the Maruts and the Ushmapās, the hosts of Gandharvas, Yakshas, Asuras and Siddhas, all gaze on Thee, all amazed.',
  '11.23': 'Having seen Thy mighty Form, with many mouths and eyes, O mighty-armed, with many arms, thighs and feet, with many torsos, with many terrible tusks, the worlds are tremulous, and so am I.',
  '11.24': 'When I see Thee, touching the heavens, glowing, many-hued, with opened mouths, with shining vast eyes, my inmost soul trembles in fear, and I find nor courage nor tranquillity, O Vishṇu!',
  '11.25': 'When I see Thy mouths terrible with tusks, like Time\'s devouring flames, I lose sense of the directions, and find no peace. Have mercy, O Lord of gods, refuge of the worlds!',
  '11.26': 'All these sons of Dhṛitarāshṭra, with the hosts of princes, Bhīshma, Droṇa and Sūta\'s son, with also our chief warriors,',
  '11.27': 'Are rushing into Thy mouths, terror-striking with terrific tusks. Some are seen, with pulverised heads, sticking in the gaps between Thy teeth.',
  '11.28': 'As the many torrents of the rivers flow towards the ocean, so these heroes of the world of men enter Thy flaming mouths.',
  '11.29': 'As moths swiftly rushing enter a burning fire to perish, so also these enter Thy mouths swiftly to their own destruction.',
  '11.30': 'Devouring all the worlds on every side with Thy flaming mouths, Thou lickest them up. Thy fierce rays, filling the whole world with radiance, are burning, O Vishṇu!',
  '11.31': 'Reveal to me who Thou art in this fierce form. Salutations be to Thee, O God supreme! have mercy. I desire to know Thee, the Primal One; for I know not Thy working.',
  '11.32': 'The Blessed Lord said: Time am I, laying desolate the world, made manifest on earth to slay mankind. Not one of all these warriors arrayed in hostile armies shall live, save thou.',
  '11.33': 'Therefore stand up, win for thyself renown, conquer the foes, and enjoy the opulent kingdom; by Me Themselves are they slain already; be thou merely the outward cause, O Savyasāchin.',
  '11.34': 'Slay Droṇa and Bhīshma and Jayadratha, Karṇa and the other heroic warriors, slain verily by Me. Be not distressed. Fight! Thou shalt conquer thy foes in the battle.',
  '11.35': 'Sañjaya said: Having heard these words of Keshava, the diademed Arjuna, with joined palms, trembling, prostrating himself, again addressed Kṛishṇa, stammering, bowed down with fear.',
  '11.36': 'Arjuna said: It is meet, O Hṛishīkesha, that in praise of Thee the world rejoiceth and is gratified; the Rākshasas flee in fear in all directions, and all the hosts of the Siddhas bow down before Thee.',
  '11.37': 'And wherefore should they not bow down to Thee, O mighty-souled, greater than Brahmā, primal Cause? O Infinite Being, Lord of gods, Refuge of the universe, Thou the Imperishable, beyond being and non-being.',
  '11.38': 'Thou the primal God, the ancient Purusha; Thou of this universe the supreme Receptacle; Thou the Knower and the Knowable, the supreme Goal, and by Thee is the universe pervaded, O boundless Form!',
  '11.39': 'Vāyu, Yama, Agni, Varuṇa, the Moon, Prajāpati art Thou, and the Great-grandsire. Salutations, salutations unto Thee, a thousand times, and again and yet again salutations, salutations unto Thee.',
  '11.40': 'Salutation to Thee before and behind! Salutations to Thee on every side! O All! Infinite in power and infinite in prowess, Thou pervadest all, wherefore Thou art All.',
  '11.41': 'Whatsoever I have presumptuously said from carelessness or affection, addressing Thee as O Kṛishṇa, O Yādava, O Comrade, regarding Thee merely as a friend, unknowing of this Thy greatness,',
  '11.42': 'In whatever way I may have been disrespectful to Thee in jest, while at play, reposing, sitting or at meals, when alone, O unshaken One, or in company — that I implore Thee, Immeasurable, to forgive.',
  '11.43': 'Thou art the Father of the world, of moving and unmoving things; Thou its object of worship, and most venerable Guru. None is equal to Thee; how then a greater than Thee in the Three Worlds, O Being of unequalled power?',
  '11.44': 'Therefore bowing down, prostrating my body, I crave Thy mercy, Lord adorable! As father with the son, as friend with the friend, as lover with the beloved, deign, O Lord, to bear with me.',
  '11.45': 'I am rejoiced that I have seen what was never seen before, and yet my mind is distracted with terror. Show me, O God, that other Form. Have mercy, O Lord of gods, Refuge of the worlds!',
  '11.46': 'I would see Thee even as before, crowned, bearing the mace and discus in Thy hand. Wear that Thy four-armed shape, O Thousand-armed, O Universal Form!',
  '11.47': 'The Blessed Lord said: By favour to thee, O Arjuna, hath been shown this supreme Form, by My sovereign Yoga. This Form of Mine resplendent, universal, primaeval, infinite, hath not been seen by any save thee.',
  '11.48': 'Nor by study of the Vedas, nor by sacrifices, nor by gifts, nor by ritual, nor by severe austerities, can I in such a Form be seen in the world of men by any other than thee, O hero of the Kurus.',
  '11.49': 'Be not afraid, nor bewildered in beholding this terrific Form of Mine. Banishing fear and with gladdened heart, again behold this My familiar Form, O thee.',
  '11.50': 'Sañjaya said: Vāsudeva, having thus spoken to Arjuna, again manifested His own Form; and the Mahātmā, having again assumed His gracious shape, comforted the terrified one.',
  '11.51': 'Arjuna said: Beholding again Thy gentle human Form, O Janārdana, I am now composed, and am restored to my own nature.',
  '11.52': 'The Blessed Lord said: Right hard to see is this My Form, which thou hast seen. Verily the shining Ones ever long to behold this Form.',
  '11.53': 'Nor can I be seen as thou hast seen Me, by the Vedas, nor by austerities, nor by gifts, nor by sacrifice;',
  '11.54': 'But by devotion to Me alone I may thus be perceived, Arjuna, and known and seen in essence, and entered, O Parantapa.',
  '11.55': 'He who doeth actions for Me, whose supreme Good I am, My devotee, freed from attachment, without hatred of any being, he cometh unto Me, O Pāṇḍava.',

  // ── Chapter 12 ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  '12.1': 'Those devotees who, ever harmonised, thus worship Thee, and those also who worship the Indestructible, the Unmanifested — whether of these is the more learned in yoga?',
  '12.2': 'The Blessed Lord said: Those who, with mind fixed on Me, ever harmonised, worship Me, with faith supreme endowed, these, in My eyes, are best in yoga.',
  '12.3': 'They who worship the Indestructible, the Ineffable, the Unmanifested, Omnipresent and Unthinkable, the Unchanging, Immutable, the Eternal,',
  '12.4': 'Restraining and subduing the senses, regarding everything equally, in the welfare of all rejoicing, these also come unto Me.',
  '12.5': 'The difficulty of those whose minds are set on the Unmanifested is greater; for the path of the Unmanifested is hard for the embodied to reach.',
  '12.6': 'They verily who, renouncing all actions in Me and intent on Me, worship, meditating on Me, with whole-hearted yoga,',
  '12.7': 'These I speedily lift up from the ocean of death and existence, O Pārtha, their minds being fixed on Me.',
  '12.8': 'Place thy mind in Me, into Me let thy Reason enter; then without doubt thou shalt abide in Me hereafter.',
  '12.9': 'But if thou art not able firmly to fix thy mind on Me, then by the yoga of practice seek to reach Me, O Dhanañjaya.',
  '12.10': 'If also thou art not equal to constant practice, be intent on My service; performing actions for My sake, thou shalt attain perfection.',
  '12.11': 'If even to do this thou hast not strength, then taking refuge in union with Me, renounce the fruit of all action, with the self controlled.',
  '12.12': 'Better indeed is wisdom than practice; than wisdom meditation is better; than meditation, renunciation of the fruit of action; on renunciation follows peace.',
  '12.14': 'Ever content, harmonious, with the self controlled, resolute, with mind and Reason dedicated to Me, he, My devotee, is dear to Me.',
  '12.15': 'He from whom the world doth not shrink away, who doth not shrink away from the world, freed from the anxieties of joy, anger and fear, he is dear to Me.',
  '12.16': 'He who wants nothing, is pure, expert, passionless, untroubled, renouncing every undertaking, he, My devotee, is dear to Me.',
  '12.17': 'He who neither rejoiceth nor hateth, nor grieveth, nor desireth, renouncing good and evil, full of devotion, he is dear to Me.',
  '12.18': 'Alike to foe and friend, and also in fame and ignominy, alike in cold and heat, pleasures and pains, destitute of attachment,',
  '12.19': 'Taking equally praise and reproach, silent, wholly content with what cometh, homeless, firm in mind, full of devotion, that man is dear to Me.',
  '12.20': 'They verily who partake of this life-giving wisdom as taught herein, endued with faith, I their Supreme Object, devotees, they are surpassingly dear to Me.',

  // ── Chapter 13 ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  '13.1': 'The Blessed Lord said: This body, O Kaunteya, is called Kṣetra; that which knoweth it is called Kṣetrajña by the Sages.',
  '13.2': 'And understand Me as the Kṣetrajña in all Kṣetras, O Bhārata. The knowledge of the Kṣetra and the Kṣetrajña, that in My opinion is the Wisdom.',
  '13.3': 'What that Kṣetra is, what its qualities, what its modifications, and whence are what; and also who He is, and what are His powers, that hear briefly from Me.',
  '13.4': 'Rishis have sung in many ways in various distinctive chants, and in suggestive words indicating Brahman, full of reasonings and decisive.',
  '13.5': 'The great Elements, Individuality, Reason, and the Unmanifested also, the ten senses and the one, and the five pastures of the senses,',
  '13.6': 'Desire, hatred, pleasure, pain, the aggregate, intelligence, firmness — this, briefly described, is the Kṣetra, with its modifications.',
  '13.7': 'Humility, unpretentiousness, harmlessness, forgiveness, rectitude, service of the Teacher, purity, steadfastness, self-control,',
  '13.8': 'Indifference to the objects of the senses, and also absence of egoism, insight into the pain and evil of birth, death, old age and sickness,',
  '13.9': 'Unattachment, absence of self-identification with son, wife or home, and constant balance of mind in wished-for and unwished-for events,',
  '13.10': 'And unflinching devotion to Me by yoga, without other object, resort to sequestered places, absence of enjoyment in the company of men,',
  '13.11': 'Constancy in the Wisdom of the Self, understanding of the object of essential wisdom; that is declared to be the Wisdom; all against it is ignorance.',
  '13.12': 'I will declare that which ought to be known, that which being known immortality is enjoyed — the beginningless supreme ETERNAL, called neither being nor non-being.',
  '13.13': 'Everywhere THAT hath hands and feet, everywhere eyes, heads, and mouths; all-hearing, He dwelleth in the world, enveloping all;',
  '13.14': 'Shining with all sense-faculties without any senses; unattached supporting everything, and free from qualities enjoying qualities;',
  '13.15': 'Without and within all beings, immovable and also movable; by reason of His subtlety imperceptible; at hand and far away is THAT.',
  '13.16': 'Not divided amid beings, and yet seated distributively; that is to be known as the Supporter of beings; He devoureth and He generateth.',
  '13.17': 'That, the Light of all lights, is said to be beyond darkness; Wisdom, the Object of Wisdom, by Wisdom to be reached, seated in the hearts of all.',
  '13.18': 'Thus the Kṣetra, Wisdom and the Object of Wisdom have been briefly told. My devotee, thus knowing, entereth into My being.',
  '13.19': 'Know thou that Matter and Spirit are both without beginning; and know thou also that modifications and qualities are all Matter-born.',
  '13.20': 'In the production of effect and cause, Matter is said to be the cause; in the experience of pleasure and pain, Spirit is said to be the cause.',
  '13.21': 'Spirit, seated in Matter, useth the qualities born of Matter; attachment to the qualities is the cause of his births in good and evil wombs.',
  '13.22': 'The Supervisor and Permitter, the Supporter, Enjoyer, the mighty Lord, and also called the Supreme Self, is the supreme Spirit in this body.',
  '13.23': 'He who thus knoweth Spirit and Matter with its qualities, in whatsoever condition he may be, he is not born again.',
  '13.24': 'Some by meditation behold the Self in the self by the Self; others by the Sāṅkhya yoga, and others by the yoga of action;',
  '13.25': 'Yet others, ignorant of this, having heard from others, worship; they also cross over death, devoted to what they have heard.',
  '13.26': 'Wherever a being is born, immovable or movable, know thou, O best of the Bhāratas, that it is from the union of Kṣetra with Kṣetrajña.',
  '13.27': 'Seated equally in all beings, the supreme Lord, unperishing within the perishing — he who thus seeth, he seeth.',
  '13.28': 'Seeing indeed everywhere the equally-seated Lord, he destroyeth not the Self by the self, and thus treadeth the highest Path.',
  '13.29': 'And he who seeth all actions performed by Matter alone, and likewise the Self not the doer, he seeth.',
  '13.30': 'When he perceiveth the diversified existence of beings as rooted in One, and spreading forth from It alone, he then reacheth the ETERNAL.',
  '13.31': 'Beginningless, devoid of qualities, this supreme Self, imperishable, although seated in the body, O Kaunteya, neither acteth nor is affected.',
  '13.32': 'As the omnipresent ether, by reason of its subtlety, is not soiled, so seated everywhere in the body the Self is not soiled.',
  '13.33': 'As the one Sun illumineth the whole earth, so the Lord of the Kṣetra illumineth the whole Kṣetra, O Bhārata.',
  '13.34': 'They who by the eye of Wisdom perceive this difference between the Kṣetra and the Kṣetrajña, and the liberation of beings from Matter, they go to the Supreme.',
  '13.35': 'They who by the eye of Wisdom thus perceive the distinction between Kṣetra and the Kṣetrajña, and the deliverance of beings from Matter, they go unto the Supreme.',

  // ── Chapter 14 ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  '14.1': 'The Blessed Lord said: I will again proclaim that supreme Wisdom, of all wisdom the best, which all the Munis having known, have gone hence to supreme perfection.',
  '14.2': 'They who, having taken refuge in this Wisdom, have entered into a nature similar to Mine, are not born even in the emanation of a universe, nor are disturbed in the dissolution.',
  '14.3': 'My womb is the great ETERNAL; in that I place the germ; thence cometh the birth of all beings, O Bhārata.',
  '14.4': 'In whatsoever wombs mortals are produced, O Kaunteya, the great ETERNAL is their womb, I the generating Father.',
  '14.5': 'Harmony, Motion, Inertia — such are the qualities, Matter-born; they bind fast in the body, O great-armed one, the indestructible dweller in the body.',
  '14.6': 'Of these, Harmony, from its stainlessness, luminous and healthy, bindeth by the attachment to bliss and the attachment to wisdom, O sinless one.',
  '14.7': 'Motion, know thou, of the nature of passion, the source of thirst and attachment, it bindeth fast, O Kaunteya, the embodied one by the attachment to action.',
  '14.8': 'But Inertia, know thou, born of unwisdom, is the deluder of all embodied beings; it bindeth fast, O Bhārata, by heedlessness, indolence and slumber.',
  '14.9': 'Harmony attacheth to bliss, Motion to action, O Bhārata; Inertia, verily, having shrouded wisdom, attacheth on the contrary to heedlessness.',
  '14.10': 'Now Harmony prevaileth, having overpowered Motion and Inertia, O Bhārata; now Motion, having overpowered Harmony and Inertia; and now Inertia, having overpowered Harmony and Motion.',
  '14.11': 'When the wisdom-light streameth forth from all the gates of the body, then it may be known that Harmony is increasing.',
  '14.12': 'Greed, outgoing energy, undertaking of actions, restlessness, desire — these are born of the increase of Motion, O best of the Bhāratas.',
  '14.13': 'Darkness, stagnation and heedlessness, and also delusion — these are born of the increase of Inertia, O joy of the Kurus.',
  '14.14': 'If Harmony prevaileth when the embodied goeth to dissolution, then he reacheth the spotless worlds of the Knowers of the Highest.',
  '14.15': 'Going to dissolution in Motion, he is born among those attached to action; if dissolved in Inertia, he is born in the wombs of the senseless.',
  '14.16': 'It is said the fruit of good action is harmonious and spotless; verily the fruit of Motion is pain, and the fruit of Inertia unwisdom.',
  '14.17': 'From Harmony Wisdom is born, and also Greed from Motion; heedlessness and delusion are of Inertia, and also unwisdom.',
  '14.18': 'They rise upwards who are settled in Harmony; the Active dwell in the midmost place; the Inert go downwards, enveloped in the vilest qualities.',
  '14.19': 'When the Seer perceiveth no agent other than the qualities, and knoweth THAT which is higher than the qualities, he entereth into My nature.',
  '14.20': 'When the embodied one crosseth over these three qualities whence all bodies have been produced, liberated from birth, death, old age and sorrow, he drinketh the nectar of immortality.',
  '14.21': 'Arjuna said: What are the marks of him who hath crossed over the three qualities, O Lord? How acteth he, and how doth he go beyond these three qualities?',
  '14.22': 'The Blessed Lord said: He who hateth not radiance, nor outgoing energy, nor even delusion, O Pāṇḍava, when present, nor longeth after them when absent;',
  '14.23': 'He who, seated as a neutral, is unshaken by the qualities; who saying: "the qualities revolve," standeth apart, immovable,',
  '14.24': 'Balanced in pleasure and pain, self-reliant, to whom a lump of earth, a rock and gold are alike; the same to loved and unloved, firm, the same in censure and in praise,',
  '14.25': 'The same in honour and ignominy, the same to friend and foe, abandoning all undertakings — he is said to have crossed over the qualities.',
  '14.26': 'And he who serveth Me exclusively by the yoga of devotion, he, crossing beyond the qualities, is fit to become the ETERNAL.',
  '14.27': 'For I am the abode of the ETERNAL, and of the indestructible nectar of immortality, and of the immemorial Dharma, and of unending bliss.',

  // ── Chapter 15 ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  '15.1': 'With roots above, branches below, the Aśvattha is said to be indestructible; its leaves are hymns; he who knoweth it is a Veda-knower.',
  '15.2': 'Downwards and upwards spread its branches, nourished by the qualities; the sense-objects its twigs; and downwards in the world of men stretch forth its roots, originating action.',
  '15.3': 'Its form is not thus understood here, nor its end, nor its origin, nor its foundation. Having cut this strongly-rooted Aśvattha by the strong axe of non-attachment,',
  '15.4': 'Then That Path must be sought after, treading which they return no more: I go indeed to that Primal Man whence the ancient energy forth-streamed.',
  '15.5': 'Without pride or delusion, victorious over the vice of attachment, dwelling constantly in the Self, desires having utterly retreated, liberated from the pairs of opposites known as pleasure and pain, they tread, undeluded, that imperishable path.',
  '15.6': 'Nor doth the sun illumine That, nor moon, nor fire; having gone thither they return not; that is My supreme abode.',
  '15.7': 'A portion of Mine own Self, transformed in the world of life into an immortal Spirit, draweth round itself the senses of which the mind is the sixth, veiled in matter.',
  '15.8': 'When the Lord taketh a body and when He forsaketh it, He seizeth these and goeth with them, as the wind takes fragrances from their retreats.',
  '15.9': 'Enshrined in the ear, the eye, touch, taste and smell, and in the mind also, He enjoyeth the objects of the senses.',
  '15.10': 'The deluded do not perceive Him when leaving or staying in the body, or enjoying, swayed by the qualities; the wisdom-eyed perceive.',
  '15.11': 'The Yogīs, struggling, perceive Him established in the Self; but the unintelligent, ill-disciplined, though struggling, perceive Him not.',
  '15.12': 'That splendour issuing from the sun that enlighteneth the whole world, that which is in the moon, that which is in fire, that splendour know as from Me.',
  '15.13': 'Permeating the soil, I support beings by My vital energy; and, having become the watery moon, I nourish all herbs.',
  '15.14': 'I, having become the Vaiśvānara fire, abide in the body of breathing creatures, and, mingled with the upward and downward life-breaths, digest the four kinds of food.',
  '15.15': 'And I am seated in the hearts of all; from Me memory and wisdom and their absence. I alone am the object to be known by all the Vedas; I am indeed the Author of the Vedānta and the Veda-knower am I.',
  '15.16': 'There are two Puruṣas in this world, the perishable and the imperishable; the perishable is all beings, the unchanging is called the imperishable.',
  '15.17': 'But other than these, the highest Puruṣa, called the Supreme Self, the indestructible Lord, who pervading sustaineth the three worlds.',
  '15.18': 'Since I excel the perishable, and am more excellent also than the imperishable, in the world and in the Veda I am proclaimed Puruṣottama (the highest Spirit).',
  '15.19': 'He who undeluded thus knoweth Me, the highest Spirit, he, knowing all, worshippeth Me with his whole being, O Bhārata.',
  '15.20': 'Thus this most secret Śāstra hath been taught by Me, sinless one. This being known, he will have known, and have done his work, O Bhārata.',

  // ── Chapter 16 ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  '16.1': 'Fearlessness, cleanness of life, steadfastness in the Yoga of wisdom, almsgiving, self-restraint and sacrifice and study of the Scriptures, austerity and straightforwardness,',
  '16.2': 'Harmlessness, truth, absence of wrath, renunciation, peacefulness, absence of crookedness, compassion to living beings, uncovetousness, mildness, modesty, absence of fickleness,',
  '16.3': 'Vigour, forgiveness, fortitude, purity, absence of envy and pride — these are his who is born with the divine properties, O Bhārata.',
  '16.4': 'Hypocrisy, arrogance and conceit, wrath and also harshness and unwisdom, are his, O Pārtha, who is born with demoniacal properties.',
  '16.5': 'The divine properties are deemed to be for liberation, the demoniacal for bondage. Grieve not, O Pāṇḍava, thou art born with the divine properties.',
  '16.6': 'Twofold is the animal creation in this world, the divine and the demoniacal; the divine hath been described at length; hear from Me, O Pārtha, the demoniacal.',
  '16.7': 'The demoniacal know neither right energy nor right abstinence; nor purity, nor even propriety, nor truth is in them.',
  '16.8': '"The universe is without truth, without basis, without a God," they say; "not produced by mutual causation, caused only by lust."',
  '16.9': 'Holding this view, these ruined Selves of small understanding, of fierce deeds, come forth as enemies for the destruction of the world.',
  '16.10': 'Surrendering themselves to insatiable desires, possessed with vanity, conceit and arrogance, holding evil ideas through delusion, they engage in action with impure resolves.',
  '16.11': 'Giving themselves over to unmeasured thought whose end is death, regarding the gratification of desires as the highest, feeling sure that this is all,',
  '16.12': 'Held in bondage by a hundred ties of expectation, given over to lust and anger, they strive to obtain by unlawful means hoards of wealth for sensual enjoyments.',
  '16.13': '"This to-day by me hath been won, that purpose I shall gain; this wealth is mine already, and also this shall be mine in future;',
  '16.14': '"I have slain this enemy, and others also I shall slay. I am the lord, I am the enjoyer, I am perfect, powerful, happy;',
  '16.15': '"I am wealthy, well-born; what other is there that is like unto me? I will sacrifice, I will give, I will rejoice." Thus deluded by unwisdom,',
  '16.16': 'Bewildered by numerous thoughts, enmeshed in the web of delusion, attached to the gratification of desire, they fall downwards into a foul hell.',
  '16.17': 'Self-glorifying, stubborn, filled with the pride and intoxication of wealth, they perform lip-sacrifices for ostentation, contrary to scriptural ordinance.',
  '16.18': 'Given over to egoism, power, insolence, lust and wrath, these malignants hate Me in the bodies of others and in their own.',
  '16.19': 'These haters, evil, pitiless, vilest among men in the world, I ever throw down into demoniacal wombs.',
  '16.20': 'Cast into a demoniacal womb, deluded birth after birth, attaining not to Me, O Kaunteya, they sink into the lowest depths.',
  '16.21': 'Triple is the gate of this hell, destructive of the Self — lust, wrath, and greed; therefore let man renounce these three.',
  '16.22': 'A man liberated from these three gates of darkness, O Kaunteya, accomplisheth his own welfare, and thus reacheth the highest goal.',
  '16.23': 'He who, having cast aside the ordinances of the Scriptures, followeth the promptings of desire, attaineth not to perfection, nor happiness, nor the highest goal.',
  '16.24': 'Therefore let the Scriptures be thy authority in determining what ought to be done, or what ought not to be done. Knowing what hath been declared by the ordinances of the Scriptures, thou oughtest to work in this world.',

  // ── Chapter 17 ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  '17.1': 'Those who, setting aside the ordinances of the Scriptures, sacrifice full of faith — what is their condition, O Kṛṣṇa? Sattva, Rajas or Tamas?',
  '17.2': 'Threefold is the faith of the embodied, which is inherent in their nature — Sāttvic, Rājasic and Tāmasic. Hear thou of it.',
  '17.3': 'The faith of each is shaped to his own nature, O Bhārata. The man is made up of his faith; as a man\'s faith is, so is he.',
  '17.4': 'Sāttvic men worship the Devas; Rājasic, the Yakṣas and Rākṣasas; others, Tāmasic, worship elementals and ghosts.',
  '17.5': 'Men who perform severe austerities not enjoined by the Scriptures, given over to hypocrisy and egoism, impelled by the force of their desires and passions,',
  '17.6': 'Unintelligent, torturing the aggregated elements forming the body, and Me also, seated in the inner body, know these demoniacal in their resolves.',
  '17.7': 'The food also which is dear to each is threefold, as also sacrifice, austerity and almsgiving. Hear thou the distinction of these.',
  '17.8': 'The foods which augment vitality, energy, vigour, health, joy and cheerfulness, which are delicious, bland, substantial and agreeable, are dear to the Sāttvic.',
  '17.9': 'The passionate desire foods that are bitter, sour, saline, excessively hot, pungent, dry and burning, and which produce pain, grief and disease.',
  '17.10': 'That which is stale and flat, putrid and corrupt, leavings also and unclean, is the food dear to the Tāmasic.',
  '17.11': 'The sacrifice which is offered according to ordinance, by men desiring no fruit, the mind being satisfied that it is duty to sacrifice, that is Sāttvic.',
  '17.12': 'But that which is offered in expectation of reward and for the sake of ostentation, know thou that sacrifice to be Rājasic, O best of the Bhāratas.',
  '17.13': 'They declare that sacrifice to be Tāmasic which is contrary to ordinance, with no food distributed, devoid of mantras and gifts, void of faith.',
  '17.14': 'Worship given to the gods, to the twice-born, to teachers and to the wise, purity, straightforwardness, continence and harmlessness, are called the austerity of the body.',
  '17.15': 'Speech causing no annoyance, truthful, pleasant and beneficial, the practice of the study of the Scriptures, are called the austerity of speech.',
  '17.16': 'Mental happiness, equilibrium, silence, self-control, purity of nature — this is called the austerity of the mind.',
  '17.17': 'This threefold austerity, performed by men with the utmost faith, desiring no fruit, harmonised, is said to be Sāttvic.',
  '17.18': 'The austerity which is performed for the sake of gaining respect, honour and worship, and with hypocrisy, is here said to be Rājasic, unstable and transitory.',
  '17.19': 'The austerity which is performed with foolish obstinacy, with self-torture, or for destroying another, that is declared to be Tāmasic.',
  '17.20': 'That gift which is given, knowing it to be a duty, in a fit place and time, to a worthy person, from whom we expect nothing again, is held to be Sāttvic.',
  '17.21': 'And that which is given with a view to receive in return, or for the sake of a future reward, or grudgingly, that is held to be Rājasic.',
  '17.22': 'The gift that is given at a wrong place or time, to unworthy persons, without respect or with contempt, that is declared to be Tāmasic.',
  '17.23': 'OM TAT SAT — this hath been declared the triple designation of the eternal. By that were ordained of old the Brāhmaṇas, the Vedas and the sacrifices.',
  '17.24': 'Therefore, with the utterance of OM, the acts of sacrifice, gift and austerity, enjoined in the ordinances, are always begun by the students of the Brahman.',
  '17.25': 'With "TAT," without aiming at the fruits, the various acts of sacrifice, austerity and gift are performed by the seekers after liberation.',
  '17.26': 'The word "SAT" is used in the sense of reality and of goodness; and so also, O Pārtha, the word "SAT" is used in the sense of an auspicious act.',
  '17.27': 'Steadfastness in sacrifice, in austerity and in almsgiving is also called "SAT," and the action which is for the sake of these is also indeed called "SAT."',
  '17.28': 'Whatsoever is wrought without faith, oblation, gift, austerity, or whatever else is done, is called "asat," O Pārtha; it is naught here or hereafter.',

  // ── Chapter 18 ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  '18.1': 'I desire, O mighty-armed, to know severally the essence of renunciation, O Hṛṣīkeśa, and of relinquishment, O Keśiniṣūdana.',
  '18.2': 'The renunciation of works of desire the sages have called renunciation; the relinquishment of the fruit of all action the wise call relinquishment.',
  '18.3': '"Action should be relinquished as an evil," some philosophers declare; "acts of sacrifice, gift and austerity are not to be relinquished," say others.',
  '18.4': 'Hear thou My conclusion as to that relinquishment, O best of Bhāratas. Relinquishment, verily, O tiger among men, hath been described as threefold.',
  '18.5': 'Acts of sacrifice, gift and austerity should not be relinquished, but should be performed; sacrifice, gift and also austerity are the purifiers of the wise.',
  '18.6': 'But even these actions should be performed, leaving aside attachment and fruit, O Pārtha; that is My certain and best belief.',
  '18.7': 'Verily the renunciation of obligatory action is not seemly. The relinquishment thereof from delusion is declared to be Tāmasic.',
  '18.8': '"It is pain," and if one relinquisheth action from fear of bodily suffering, he performeth a Rājasic relinquishment, and gaineth not the fruit of relinquishment.',
  '18.9': 'When obligatory work is performed, O Arjuna, only because it ought to be done, leaving attachment and fruit, such relinquishment is regarded as Sāttvic.',
  '18.10': 'The relinquisher pervaded with Sattva and resolute, with doubts cut away, hateth not unpleasant action nor is attached to pleasant.',
  '18.11': 'Nor indeed can embodied beings completely relinquish action; verily he who relinquisheth the fruit of action, he is said to be a relinquisher.',
  '18.12': 'Good, evil and mixed — threefold is the fruit of action hereafter for the non-relinquisher; but there is none ever for the renouncer.',
  '18.13': 'Learn of Me, O mighty-armed, these five causes, for the accomplishment of all actions, declared in the Sānkhya truth.',
  '18.14': 'The body, the actor, the various organs, the divers and distinct movements, and the presiding deities also, the fifth of these.',
  '18.15': 'Whatever action a man performeth by his body, speech and mind, whether right or the reverse, these five are the cause thereof.',
  '18.16': 'That being so, verily he who, owing to untrained reason, looketh on the Self, which is alone, as the actor, he, of perverted intelligence, seeth not.',
  '18.17': 'He whose nature is free from egoism, whose reason is not affected, though he slay these people, he slayeth not, nor is bound.',
  '18.18': 'Knowledge, the known, the knower, the threefold impulse to action; the organ, the action, the actor, the threefold is the totality of action.',
  '18.19': 'Knowledge and action and the actor are of three kinds only, according to difference of qualities, declared in the science of qualities. Hear thou of these also duly.',
  '18.20': 'That by which the one indestructible Being is seen in all beings, inseparate in the separated, know thou that knowledge as Sāttvic.',
  '18.21': 'That knowledge which seeth in all beings, separately, various entities of distinct kinds, know thou that knowledge as Rājasic.',
  '18.22': 'But that which clingeth to one single effect as if it were the whole, without reason, without foundation in truth, and trivial, that is declared to be Tāmasic.',
  '18.23': 'An action which is right, done without attachment, performed without love or hatred by one undesirous of fruit, that is called Sāttvic.',
  '18.24': 'But action which is done by one longing for desires, or again with egoism, or with much effort, that is declared to be Rājasic.',
  '18.25': 'The action undertaken from delusion, regardless of consequence, loss, injury and ability, that is declared to be Tāmasic.',
  '18.26': 'Liberated from attachment, not egoistic, endowed with firmness and vigour, unaffected in success or failure — that actor is called Sāttvic.',
  '18.27': 'Passionate, desirous of the fruit of action, greedy, malignant, impure, moved by joy and sorrow, such an actor is said to be Rājasic.',
  '18.28': 'Unbalanced, vulgar, arrogant, dishonest, malicious, indolent, despondent and procrastinating, such an actor is called Tāmasic.',
  '18.29': 'Hear thou the triple division of reason and of firmness, according to the qualities, O Dhanañjaya, declared fully and severally.',
  '18.30': 'That which knoweth energy and abstinence, what ought to be done and what ought not to be done, fear and fearlessness, bondage and liberation, that reason is Sāttvic, O Pārtha.',
  '18.31': 'That by which one understandeth wrongly right and unright, and also what ought to be done and what ought not to be done, that reason, O Pārtha, is Rājasic.',
  '18.32': 'That which, enwrapped in darkness, taketh unright as right, and seeth all things subverted, that reason, O Pārtha, is Tāmasic.',
  '18.33': 'The unwavering firmness by which, through Yoga, the functions of the mind, the life-breaths, and the senses are restrained, that firmness, O Pārtha, is Sāttvic.',
  '18.34': 'The firmness, O Arjuna, by which one holdeth to duty, pleasure and wealth, desiring fruit from each in its turn, that firmness, O Pārtha, is Rājasic.',
  '18.35': 'That by which a stupid man doth not abandon sleep, fear, grief, depression and also conceit, that firmness, O Pārtha, is Tāmasic.',
  '18.36': 'And now hear from Me, O lord of the Bhāratas, of the threefold pleasure in which one delighteth by practice and assuredly cometh to the end of pain.',
  '18.37': 'That which is like poison at first, like nectar at the end, that pleasure is declared to be Sāttvic, born of the blissful knowledge of the Self.',
  '18.38': 'That which is like nectar at first from the contact of the senses with their objects, like poison at the end, that pleasure is recorded as Rājasic.',
  '18.39': 'That pleasure which both at first and afterwards is delusive of the Self, arising from sleep, sloth and heedlessness, that is declared to be Tāmasic.',
  '18.40': 'There is no entity, on earth, or again among the gods in heaven, which is liberated from these three qualities, born of Prakṛti.',
  '18.41': 'Of Brāhmaṇas and Kṣattriyas and Vaiśyas, as also of Śūdras, O Paraṁtapa, the duties have been distributed according to the qualities born of their own natures.',
  '18.42': 'Serenity, self-restraint, austerity, purity, forgiveness and also uprightness, knowledge, realisation, belief in God, are the Brāhmaṇa-duty, born of his own nature.',
  '18.43': 'Prowess, splendour, firmness, dexterity, and also not flying from battle, generosity, the nature of a ruler, are the Kṣattriya-duty, born of his own nature.',
  '18.44': 'Ploughing, protection of cattle, and trade are the Vaiśya-duty, born of his own nature. Action of the nature of service is the Śūdra-duty, born of his own nature.',
  '18.45': 'Man reacheth perfection by each being intent on his own duty. Listen thou how perfection is won by him who is intent on his own duty.',
  '18.46': 'He from whom is the emanation of beings, by whom all this is pervaded — by worshipping Him in his own duty, man attaineth perfection.',
  '18.47': 'Better one\'s own duty, though destitute of merits, than the duty of another well discharged. He who doeth the duty laid down by his own nature incurreth not sin.',
  '18.48': 'Congenital duty, O Kaunteya, though defective, ought not to be abandoned. All undertakings indeed are clouded by defects as fire by smoke.',
  '18.49': 'He whose reason is unattached everywhere, who hath subdued the Self, from whom desire hath fled, he goeth, by renunciation, to the supreme perfection of freedom from action.',
  '18.50': 'How he who hath attained perfection findeth the Eternal, that, in brief, learn from Me, O Kaunteya — that supreme consummation of wisdom.',
  '18.51': 'United to pure reason, controlling the self by firmness, having abandoned sound and other objects of the senses, casting aside passion and malice;',
  '18.52': 'Dwelling in solitude, eating but little, speech and body and mind subdued, constantly fixed in meditation and Yoga, taking refuge in dispassion;',
  '18.53': 'Having cast aside egoism, violence, arrogance, desire, wrath, covetousness, selfless and peaceful — he is fit to become the Eternal.',
  '18.54': 'Becoming the Eternal, serene-Selved, he neither grieveth nor desireth; the same to all beings, he obtaineth supreme devotion to Me.',
  '18.55': 'By devotion he knoweth Me in essence, who and what I am; having thus known Me in essence he forthwith entereth into the Supreme.',
  '18.56': 'Although ever performing all actions, taking refuge in Me, by My grace he obtaineth the eternal indestructible abode.',
  '18.57': 'Renouncing mentally all actions in Me, intent on Me, resorting to Yoga-by-reason, have thy thought ever on Me.',
  '18.58': 'Thinking on Me, thou shalt overcome all obstacles by My grace; but if from egoism thou wilt not hear, thou shalt utterly perish.',
  '18.59': 'If, entrenched in egoism, thou thinkest, "I will not fight," to no purpose is thy determination; nature will constrain thee.',
  '18.60': 'O son of Kuntī, bound by thine own duty, born of thine own nature, that which from delusion thou desirest not to do, even that helplessly thou shalt perform.',
  '18.61': 'The Lord dwelleth in the hearts of all beings, O Arjuna, by His illusive power, causing all beings to revolve, as though mounted on a potter\'s wheel.',
  '18.62': 'Flee unto Him for shelter with all thy being, O Bhārata; by His grace thou shalt obtain supreme peace, the everlasting dwelling-place.',
  '18.63': 'Thus hath wisdom, more secret than secrecy itself, been declared unto thee by Me; having reflected on it fully, then act thou as thou listest.',
  '18.64': 'Hear thou again My supreme word, most secret of all; beloved art thou of Me and steadfast-hearted, therefore will I speak for thy benefit.',
  '18.65': 'Merge thy mind in Me, be My devotee, sacrifice to Me, prostrate thyself before Me, thou shalt come even to Me. I pledge thee My troth; thou art dear to Me.',
  '18.67': 'Never is this to be spoken by thee to one without austerities, nor without devotion, nor to one who desireth not to listen, nor yet to him who speaketh evil of Me.',
  '18.68': 'He who shall declare this supreme secret to My devotees, showing the highest devotion to Me, without doubt he shall come to Me.',
  '18.69': 'And among men there is none that doeth dearer service to Me, nor shall there be another dearer to Me in the world than he.',
  '18.70': 'And he who shall study this sacred dialogue of ours, by him I shall have been worshipped with the sacrifice of wisdom; such is My mind.',
  '18.71': 'And the man also full of faith and free from cavilling who may but hear it, even he, liberated, shall attain the radiant worlds of the righteous.',
  '18.72': 'Hath this been heard by thee, O Pārtha, with mind one-pointed? Hath thy delusion, caused by unwisdom, been destroyed, O Dhanañjaya?',
  '18.73': 'Destroyed is my delusion. I have gained knowledge through Thy grace, O Acyuta. I am firm, with doubts dispelled. I will do according to Thy word.',
  '18.74': 'Thus have I heard this marvellous dialogue between Vāsudeva and the high-souled Pārtha, causing my hair to stand on end.',
  '18.75': 'By the grace of Vyāsa I have heard this supreme secret, this Yoga, from Kṛṣṇa Himself, the Lord of Yoga, declaring it Himself in person.',
  '18.76': 'O King, remembering, remembering this marvellous and holy dialogue between Keśava and Arjuna, I rejoice again and again.',
  '18.77': 'And remembering, remembering, that most marvellous form of Hari, great is my wonder, O King; and I rejoice again and again.',
  '18.78': 'Wherever is Kṛṣṇa, the Lord of Yoga, wherever is Pārtha, the archer, there are prosperity, victory, happiness and steady policy; such is my conviction.',
};
